---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What are the three most common splashback choices in Canberra kitchens?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Across the jobs we run in any given quarter, the split is roughly: porcelain or ceramic tile (about 45%), toughened glass in a custom colour (about 30%), and a full-height stone splashback that matches or contrasts with the benchtop (about 25%). Mirror and stainless splashbacks still appear occasionally — usually in apartments around Kingston Foreshore and Civic where a small kitchen benefits from reflected light — but they account for less than 5% of installs. Each option suits different priorities: tile is the most cost-effective and the easiest to repair; glass is the easiest to clean and the most contemporary; stone gives the most considered, designed look and is favoured in higher-end Inner South homes." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What does each splashback option cost installed in 2026?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "As a 2026 supplied-and-installed guide for an average Canberra kitchen with around 4 m² of splashback: tile runs $1,400–$3,500 depending on the tile (subway $35/m² up to handmade Moroccan zellige $300/m²) plus tiler labour around $90–$130/m²; toughened painted glass in a custom RAL colour is typically $2,800–$4,200 (single piece preferred, butt-jointed if the run exceeds 3.2 m); a porcelain or sintered-stone full-height splashback to match the benchtop is $3,200–$6,500; natural stone (granite, marble, quartzite) full-height is $3,800–$8,500 depending on stone selection and bookmatching. Behind a gas cooktop we recommend tile or stone rather than glass for cleaner heat performance over time." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Is glass safe to use behind a gas cooktop in a Canberra cold-climate kitchen?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Toughened glass is certified for use behind both gas and electric cooktops under AS/NZS 4666 and AS/NZS 2208 — it is heat-resistant up to around 220–250°C surface temperature and the manufacturer warrants it for cooktop installation. The practical concern in Canberra's cold-climate kitchens is not safety but maintenance: gas burners throw spatter, and when condensation forms on a cold glass splashback (common in winter where in-slab hydronic heating doesn't reach the wall plane), the spatter etches into the surface over years and becomes harder to clean. We still install glass behind gas, but we also tell owners with serious gas-cooking habits that a porcelain or stone splashback will look better in ten years' time." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Which splashback saves the most on cleaning over ten years?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Toughened glass, by a wide margin. A single sheet of glass has no grout lines, no joins, and is wiped with a microfibre cloth in 30 seconds. Tile is the highest-maintenance option: grout discolours with cooking oil over 5–7 years and needs either re-grouting or a deep clean every couple of years, and the cost of that work over a decade is real money. Full-height stone is somewhere between — it has a join with the benchtop that needs annual silicone refresh, but otherwise wipes clean like glass. If you cook a lot and hate cleaning, glass is the answer. If you love the look of tile, plan on either an epoxy grout (more expensive to install, vastly less maintenance) or expect to refresh it once a decade." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can I have a full-height stone splashback if the benchtop stone has been bookmatched?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes — and it's becoming the signature look in higher-end Canberra Inner South kitchens. Bookmatching means the fabricator takes two adjoining slabs from the same stone block and arranges them so the veining mirrors across the join. We extend that bookmatch up the wall, so the benchtop and the splashback read as one continuous piece of stone. It costs more (you're paying for matched slabs and more wastage), but on a Forrest, Yarralumla or Deakin renovation aiming for a 10–15 year hold, it's the single design move that lifts the kitchen out of standard and into considered. Confirm bookmatching availability at the stone-selection visit before the slabs are reserved." }
    }
  ]
};
---
<Layout
  title="Splashback Options in Canberra — Tile vs Glass vs Stone | Kitchen Renovations Canberra"
  description="2026 splashback pricing and trade-offs for Canberra kitchens: porcelain and ceramic tile, toughened painted glass, and full-height stone. Cost installed, heat performance behind gas cooktops, and the option that saves the most on cleaning over ten years."
  canonical="https://kitchenrenovationscanberra.com.au/splashback-options-canberra/"
>
  <Fragment slot="head">
    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)} />
  </Fragment>

  <section class="hero">
    <div class="hero-inner">
      <span class="hero-eyebrow">Tile &middot; toughened glass &middot; full-height stone &middot; bookmatched</span>
      <h1>Three <span class="accent">splashback</span> decisions, ten-year consequences.</h1>
      <p class="hero-sub">
        The splashback is one of the smallest line items in a Canberra
        kitchen renovation and one of the most visible. Here&rsquo;s what tile,
        glass and full-height stone really cost in 2026, how each one
        behaves behind a gas cooktop in a cold-climate kitchen, and which
        option saves the most on cleaning over a decade.
      </p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a class="ph-cta btn btn-primary" href="/quote/" aria-label="Call us"><span aria-hidden="true">&#9742;</span> <span class="ph-text">Tap to call</span></a>
        <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/quote/">Get a free quote</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <span class="section-eyebrow">The three options</span>
      <h2>Tile, glass, full-height stone &mdash; what each one buys you.</h2>
      <div class="divider"></div>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">
        <h3>Tile &mdash; the most cost-effective and the easiest to repair.</h3>
        <p>
          Tile is still the most-installed splashback in Canberra kitchens,
          and for good reason: the price ceiling is low, the design vocabulary
          is enormous, and a cracked tile is a 20-minute repair rather than
          a $4,000 panel replacement. White subway tile remains the default
          in rental-grade and budget Belconnen and Tuggeranong renovations.
          In owner-occupied Gungahlin and Molonglo jobs we&rsquo;re seeing
          handmade zellige in muted greens and pinks, large-format porcelain
          in stone-look finishes, and finger-tile arrangements in Inner
          North heritage kitchens.
        </p>
        <p>
          The catch is grout. Standard cement grout discolours with cooking
          oil and steam over 5&ndash;7 years and the only fixes are deep
          cleaning (limited results), grout colour-sealing (annual
          re-application) or re-grouting (genuine job). Epoxy grout solves
          all of that &mdash; it&rsquo;s impervious, doesn&rsquo;t stain, and never
          needs re-doing &mdash; but it costs about 2.5&times; cement grout to
          install and is fussier to apply. For any tile splashback we
          expect to look fresh in ten years, we strongly recommend epoxy.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Toughened glass &mdash; easiest to clean, most contemporary.</h3>
        <p>
          Painted toughened glass is the lowest-maintenance splashback
          available. One sheet, no grout, no joins. Custom RAL colour or
          metallic finishes are made to order in Sydney or Melbourne and
          shipped to the Canberra installer &mdash; lead time is around
          10&ndash;15 working days. We measure after cabinets and benchtops
          are in to guarantee a perfect fit, with cut-outs for power points
          and rangehood ducting templated in the glass shop. A 3.2&nbsp;m
          single sheet covers most kitchens; longer runs need a butt-jointed
          second piece, which is barely visible but worth knowing about.
        </p>
        <p>
          Behind a gas cooktop, glass is certified safe under AS/NZS&nbsp;4666
          and AS/NZS&nbsp;2208 but accumulates more visible spatter over
          years than a porous stone or tile. For a serious gas cook in a
          home you plan to hold long-term, stone is a better long-game.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Full-height stone &mdash; the designed look.</h3>
        <p>
          A full-height stone splashback running from benchtop to overhead
          cabinets has become the signature finish in higher-end Canberra
          kitchens &mdash; particularly in the Inner South, Reid, and the
          embassy precinct. Done in matching benchtop stone with the veining
          bookmatched across the join, it reads as one continuous piece and
          is the single most-photographed feature in a contemporary
          kitchen. Done in a contrasting stone (a green Verde Macaubas
          quartzite behind a cream Calacatta benchtop, for example), it
          becomes the focal point of the room.
        </p>
        <p>
          The trade-off is cost &mdash; full-height stone is the most
          expensive splashback option once material, fabrication and
          installation are added. It also commits you to a single stone
          choice for both surfaces, which constrains the design. For
          renovations in homes that will be sold or kept for 10&ndash;15
          years, the resale lift and the visual payoff justify the spend.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section-alt">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <span class="section-eyebrow">Heat &amp; cold-climate considerations</span>
      <h2>Canberra winters change how a splashback behaves.</h2>
      <div class="divider"></div>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">
        <p>
          Canberra has the coldest winters of any capital, and that
          changes how splashbacks perform. In-slab hydronic heating keeps
          the floor and the bottom of the cabinets warm, but the splashback
          wall plane sits well above the heated zone. On a cold July
          morning, the splashback is one of the coldest surfaces in the
          kitchen &mdash; condensation forms readily, particularly when a
          pan of water hits boiling and the room steams up. That
          condensation rolls down a glass splashback into the silicone
          bead at the bench, and into the grout lines on a tiled one.
        </p>
        <p>
          For tile, that means the grout choice matters more in Canberra
          than in warmer climates &mdash; epoxy or, at minimum, sealed
          cement grout with annual re-sealing. For glass, the silicone
          bead at the bench junction does serious work; we use a marine-
          grade neutral-cure silicone and refresh it every 3&ndash;4 years
          as part of standard maintenance. For full-height stone, the
          mitred junction with the benchtop is the failure point &mdash;
          we run a 5&nbsp;mm sealant joint and refresh annually.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <span class="section-eyebrow">Frequently asked</span>
      <h2>Splashback questions we get every week.</h2>
      <div class="divider"></div>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">
        <h3>What do the three options cost installed?</h3>
        <p>
          For about 4&nbsp;m² of splashback in 2026: tile $1,400&ndash;$3,500
          (tile $35&ndash;$300/m² plus tiler at $90&ndash;$130/m²); toughened
          glass $2,800&ndash;$4,200 in a custom RAL colour; porcelain or
          sintered-stone full-height $3,200&ndash;$6,500; natural stone
          full-height $3,800&ndash;$8,500. Bookmatched stone is at the top
          of the range.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Is glass safe behind a gas cooktop?</h3>
        <p>
          Yes, certified under AS/NZS&nbsp;4666 and AS/NZS&nbsp;2208 for use
          behind both gas and electric. The practical concern is
          maintenance &mdash; serious gas cooking throws spatter that
          etches over years, and Canberra&rsquo;s cold-climate condensation
          makes it worse. Stone or tile is a better long-game for heavy
          gas cooks.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Which option saves the most on cleaning over a decade?</h3>
        <p>
          Toughened glass &mdash; no grout, no joins, microfibre cloth in 30
          seconds. Tile is the highest maintenance unless you invest in
          epoxy grout up front. Full-height stone sits between, with a
          benchtop join that needs annual silicone refresh.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Can I bookmatch the splashback to the benchtop?</h3>
        <p>
          Yes &mdash; the fabricator reserves matched slabs from the same
          block and mirrors the veining across the join. It costs more
          (matched slabs plus wastage) but on a Forrest, Yarralumla or
          Deakin renovation aiming for a 10&ndash;15 year hold, it&rsquo;s the
          design move that lifts the kitchen out of standard.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section cta-section">
    <div class="section-inner cta-inner">
      <h2>Bring a Pinterest image &mdash; we&rsquo;ll price all three options.</h2>
      <p>
        Send us the look you want and the kitchen size, and we&rsquo;ll come
        back with tile, glass and stone pricing side-by-side so you can see
        the trade-off rather than guess at it.
      </p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a class="ph-cta btn btn-primary" href="/quote/" aria-label="Call us"><span aria-hidden="true">&#9742;</span> <span class="ph-text">Tap to call</span></a>
        <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/quote/">Email a free quote request</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
